[2
Date: Sat, 3 Oct 1998 13:22:28 EDT
From: MPrice7744@aol.com
Source; Houston Chronicle; Sat 3 Oct 1998, edited

The illness ultimately was blamed on a strain of bacterium normally found in
waters around Japan and some other Asian locations. Federal health officials
speculate that the bacterium got into Galveston Bay when a passing ship
dumped ballast water. Months of testing have failed to isolate this strain
directly from oysters in Galveston Bay however.
(Comment: While the original strain of _V. parahemolyticus_ may well be
gone, I imagine that it remains possible that the same series of events
could cause a recurrence of the problem, thus these regulations. Maybe
someone should look into the habit of dumping ballast water in shallow, low
salinity areas.)
---
Margaret F. Price,PhD
St. Luke's Hospital
Houston, TX
<MPrice7744@aol.com>
[It is interesting that even though there is an ecological continuity from
Galveston through to the easternmost Louisiana oyster beds, these
organisms caused no problems in Louisiana, which might support the
ballast hypothesis - Mod.MHJ
